author: Al Jazeera English
description:
A United Nations report warns the Israeli occupation has battered the Palestinian economy, wiping out nearly two decades of growth in just over a year.
It says Gaza’s economy is in freefall since Israel’s war began and is now worth just 13% of its value in 2022.
It also found GDP in the occupied West Bank plunged 17% last year due to Israeli military actions, with per capita income falling to 2008 levels.
The report estimated that without decades of Israeli occupation, real per capita income among Palestinians could have been 241% higher.
The UN warns the toll on the economy and ongoing violence will have a devastating effect on people and is calling for an end to the expansion of illegal Israeli settlements and the lifting of restrictions on the Palestinian economy.

Raja Khalidi is the Director General of the Palestine Economic Policy Research Institute.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Lawyer John Mbano is on a mission. His great-grandfather, Songea Mbano, a leader of the Ngoni people in southern Tanzania, was executed by the German colonial army in 1906, and his head was taken to Germany for racist scientific research.

Generations of the family have been haunted by this trauma to this day. John and his wife, Cesilia, a history teacher, embark on a life-changing journey to Berlin in search of their ancestor's skull, hoping that it can be buried with dignity back home.

The Empty Grave is a documentary film by Agnes Lisa Wegner and Cece Mlay.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Outrage is mounting in Rio de Janeiro as a controversial law offering police cash bonuses for killing alleged criminals sparks widespread criticism. 
Dubbed the "Wild West" bill, the policy has drawn condemnation from human rights advocates and families who have lost loved ones to police violence. 
The legislation, approved by state legislators, promises bonuses up to 150% of an officer’s salary for "neutralising" criminals, a move opponents argue will exacerbate violence in Brazil’s vulnerable communities.
Families of victims, including mothers who have united in protest, claim the policy incentivises extrajudicial killings and lacks accountability. 
Critics point to the devastating impact of a similar initiative in the 1990s, which reportedly resulted in a rise in executions and did little to curb crime. 
Supporters of the bill, however, say it responds to public demand for stronger measures to combat gang violence. The governor may veto the bill, but state legislators have signalle
title: Outrage in Brazil as 'Wild West' law rewards police for killing suspects

Thousands of Congolese refugees are fleeing violence in eastern Democratic Republic of Congo, with over 63,000 crossing into Uganda since January. 
At the Nyakabande transit centre in western Uganda, families recount harrowing stories of separation, sexual violence, and forced conscription by armed groups. 
Many arrive deeply traumatised, seeking safety after escaping territories controlled by the M23 rebels and other militias.
Uganda, already hosting nearly 2 million refugees, is struggling to provide assistance amidst dwindling aid funds. Refugees face uncertain futures as they are relocated to settlements far from the border, while ongoing peace talks offer little reassurance for those who have only known conflict.

Al Jazeera’s Catherine Soi reports from Nyakabande, western Uganda.

And rather than fund the camps itself, the Thai government says the refugees living there must now find their own work.

Al Jazeera’s Tony Cheng reports from Mae La refugee camp on the Thai Myanmar border.

description:
A high-level United Nations conference aimed at addressing the plight of Rohingya refugees has called for renewed global commitment to their cause. UN officials, including Volker Turk and Filippo Grande, emphasised the urgent need for action and additional funding, noting that the Rohingya humanitarian response plan is only 37 percent funded. The UN refugee agency warned that without further resources, life-saving assistance could face severe cuts, with children already dying from malnutrition and refugees risking their lives on perilous journeys at sea.
The UK pledged an additional $36 million to support Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh, but criticisms emerged over the exclusion of Rohingya voices from the conference. Civil society representatives said the discussions fell short of delivering concrete solutions, with analysts describing the event as a repetition of past rhetoric. author: Al Jazeera English
description:
US Defence Secretary Pete Hegseth has pledged to overhaul the Pentagon's approach to military preparedness, criticising what he called the influence of political correctness on the armed forces. Addressing an unprecedented assembly of over 800 generals and admirals at a US Marine base in Quantico, Virginia, Hegseth outlined plans to restore "old school" military standards, including stricter grooming policies, rigorous fitness requirements, and the revival of practices like hazing. The event, also attended by President Donald Trump, drew criticism for its cost, logistical challenges, and potential security risks.
President Trump has expanded the military's role in domestic operations, deploying National Guard troops to address crime in major cities and proposing their use in Portland, Oregon. Critics fear the increased militarisation of domestic security could set a controversial precedent. The gathering highlighted broader debates about the balance between discipline and modernisatio
title: Trump backs Hegseth’s call for tougher US military standards

description:
The Global Sumud Flotilla says its fleet has sailed into the “high-risk zone”, 150 nautical miles (278km) from Gaza, where previous flotillas were attacked or stopped by Israeli forces.
UN Special Rapporteur Francesca Albanese and Colombian President Gustavo Petro have demanded that the Flotilla be left to proceed unharmed.
Ships from Spain and Italy have been sailing with the flotilla to ensure its safe passage through international waters, while drones from Turkiye have been circling overhead, in an apparent attempt to monitor any potential attack.
As the boats near Gaza, the Sumud Flotilla has made live video available for the safety of those on board.
Israel has sworn to stop the Gaza-bound flotilla, claiming the volunteers are trying to “breach a lawful naval blockade”, but international law is clear on allowing humanitarian aid through.

Al Jazeera’s Hassan Massoud joins us live from the Gaza aid flotilla on the Mediterranean sea.

title: Sumud Flotilla determined as it nears Gaza, amid Israeli threats

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
The Congressional Budget Office (CBO) has said the shutdown will cost the US government approximately $400m a day in furlough pay.
The office estimated that about 750,000 workers will be put on furlough, although the exact number could vary depending on how long the shutdown lasts. They will receive back pay once the shutdown ends.
Members of Congress, however, will keep getting paid throughout.
Besides furlough pay, the CBO said, there could be a long-term impact on the US economy from delays in payments, compensation, lapsed contracts, and an overall fall in demand in the private sector resulting from the shutdown.
The 2018-19 shutdown during Trump’s first term as president cost the US economy approximately $3bn, or about 0.02 percent of annual GDP.

Al Jazeera’s Heidi Zhou-Castro reports from Washington, DC.

title: How much will a shutdown cost the US government?

description:
The United States government has partially shut down after last-ditch efforts by lawmakers to pass a spending bill failed.
Republicans and Democrats could not agree on how to spend money on public healthcare, and the two sides were no closer to a compromise after weeks of negotiations. 
While the US government has partially ceased operations more than a dozen times since 1980, President Donald Trump’s threats to use the funding lapse to dramatically reduce the size of the public sector have raised the prospect of greater disruption than in past shutdowns.

Al Jazeera’s Alan Fisher reports from Capitol Hill.

description:
United States President Donald Trump says Hamas has “three or four days” to respond to his Gaza ceasefire proposal, telling reporters that Israeli and Arab leaders had already accepted the plan.
“Hamas is either going to be doing it or not, and if it’s not, it’s going to be a very sad end,” Trump said at the White House on Tuesday.
Asked if there was room for negotiations on the proposal, he replied: “Not much.”
The US president also thanked Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who met with Trump on Monday in Washington, DC, “for agreeing to the plan”.
Trump’s comments come a day after the White House released a 20-point document that calls for an immediate ceasefire in the Gaza Strip, the exchange of Israeli captives held by Hamas for Palestinians in Israeli prisons and a staged Israeli withdrawal from Gaza.

Al Jazeera’s Mike Hanna reports from Washington, DC.

description:
An estimated 60 people have been confirmed killed and almost 150 injured after a powerful magnitude 6.9 earthquake struck off the coast of the central Philippine island province of Cebu.
The United States Geological Survey said the earthquake struck at 9:59pm local time on Tuesday (13:59 GMT) off Cebu Island’s northern tip near Bogo, a city of some 90,000 residents, and was followed by four earthquakes of magnitude 5 or higher in the area after the first tremor.

Al Jazeera’s Barnaby Lo reports from Manila.

“We explained to Hamas during our meeting yesterday that our primary goal is stopping the war,” he said. “Hamas acted responsibly and promised to study the plan.”
He added that what was presented on Monday was a list of “principles”, “the details of which need to be discussed”, but that Trump’s plan “achieves a primary goal of ending the war”.
